Fig.~\ref{Fig:geo_fdtd_horn_all_1} shows the FDTD model of the horn antenna. The FDTD model uses a uniform space lattice cubic $Yee $ cells having $\bigtriangleup x=$$\bigtriangleup y=$$\bigtriangleup z=$$\bigtriangleup$$(=\lambda_o/24)$. Time step $\bigtriangleup t$ is determined by (\ref{reduce_Courant_Condition_3d2}). A $15\bigtriangleup -thick$ unsplit PML is used as ABC on all six sides of the FDTD lattices. This is spaced $20\bigtriangleup$ from the closest surface of the antenna except in front of the aperture, where the spacing is $40\bigtriangleup$. The tangential electric field components along this structure are set to zero. A simple dipole antenna is used as feed of the horn antenna. The dipole is centered laterally in the waveguide and exited with the Gaussian pulse of (\ref{gaussian_pulse_1}) with $A=1$, $t_0=150\bigtriangleup t$ \& $t_\omega=25\bigtriangleup t$. It is best to choose the distance of the dipole probe to be $\lambda_g/4$ away from the terminating wall of the wave guide as described in \cite{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation}. The propagating mode is automatically developed by this model during the numerical computation. The mode propagated to the aperture of the wave guide is dictated by the cutoff frequency of the wave guide. A virtual surface (Huygen\rq s box)\index{Huygens\rq~box}\index{FDTD!Huygens\rq~box} of six-sided rectangular box (see Fig.~\ref{Fig:near_to_far_field_trans}) that completely encloses the horn antenna in the FDTD lattice is considered between the horn structure and the PML layer for the calculation of far-field H-plane radiation pattern. 


\begin{figure}[tb!]
\begin{center}
\centerline{\includegraphics[scale=0.30]{tx_mode_analysis_horn_fdtd_coordinate_syst}}
\caption{\label{Fig:tx_mode_analysis_horn_fdtd_coordinate_syst}Coordinate system for the computation of far-field horn radiation pattern.}
\end{center}
\end{figure}
The coordinate system for the calculation of far-field radiation pattern is shown in the Fig.~\ref{Fig:tx_mode_analysis_horn_fdtd_coordinate_syst}. Far-field variation with respect to $\theta$, when $\phi=0^\circ$ or $\phi=180^\circ$ gives H-plane radiation pattern of the horn antenna. When $\phi=90^\circ$ or $\phi=270^\circ$, far-field variation with respect to $\theta$ gives E-plane radiation pattern and when $\phi=0^\circ\pm\phi'$ or $\phi=180^\circ\pm\phi'$, far-field variation with respect to $\theta$ gives diagonal-plane radiation pattern of the horn antenna. Where, $\phi'$ is given by
\be\label{tx_mode_coor_syst_1}
\phi'=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{B}{A}\right)
\ee




